{
  "texts": [
    "The A α (G) matrix is the result of a convex combination between the diagonal matrix degree and the adjacency matrix, considering any 0 ≤ α ≤ 1:A α (G) = αD(G) + (1 -α)A(G).",
    "The eigenvalues of A α (G) are denoted by λ 1 (A α) ≥ λ 2 (A α) ≥... ≥ λ n (A α).The spectral radius of this matrix, denoted ρ α (G) = λ 1 (A α), is called α-index.",
    "Some important relations to be highlighted are:A(G) = A 0 (G), D(G) = A 1 (G) e Q(G) = 2A 1/2 (G).Other definitions and results on matrices and eigenvalues can be found in [1], [6] and [16].",
    "k-path graphsIn the same article that presents the inductive definition of k-trees, [21], the following characterization of these graphs is presented.",
    "A connected graph that has k-clique and has not k + 2-clique, and for which all minimal separators induce a complete graph K k is a k-tree.According to [19], k-path graphs can be defined recursively as follows: let n ≥ k and k ≥ 2, every complete graph with k vertices is a k-path graph."
  ]
}